# Code Explanation

## Node Class

```java
class Node {
    int key;
    int value;
    int freq;
    Node prev;
    Node next;
}
```

Each cache item stores:

```text
key
value
frequency count
previous pointer
next pointer
```

The `prev` and `next` pointers are used because each frequency group is stored as a doubly linked list.

---

## DoublyLinkedList Class

Each frequency has its own doubly linked list.

Example:

```text
freq 1: head <-> nodeA <-> nodeB <-> tail
freq 2: head <-> nodeC <-> tail
```

We add recently used nodes near the head.

So:

```text
head.next = most recently used node in this frequency
tail.prev = least recently used node in this frequency
```

---

## addToHead(node)

```java
public void addToHead(Node node) {
    node.next = head.next;
    node.prev = head;

    head.next.prev = node;
    head.next = node;

    size++;
}
```

This inserts a node right after `head`.

That means this node is now the most recently used node in that frequency group.

---

## remove(node)

```java
public void remove(Node node) {
    node.prev.next = node.next;
    node.next.prev = node.prev;

    size--;
}
```

This removes a node from its current frequency list.

Example:

```text
A <-> B <-> C
```

If we remove `B`, the list becomes:

```text
A <-> C
```

---

## removeTail()

```java
public Node removeTail() {
    if (size == 0) return null;

    Node node = tail.prev;
    remove(node);

    return node;
}
```

This removes the least recently used node inside that frequency list.

Because:

```text
head side = recently used
tail side = least recently used
```

So `tail.prev` is the oldest node in that frequency group.

---

# updateFrequency(node)

Whenever we call `get(key)`, that key is used one more time.

So its frequency must increase.

Example:

```text
Before get(2):

freq 1: 2, 3
freq 2: 5

After get(2):

freq 1: 3
freq 2: 2, 5
```

Code:

```java
private void updateFrequency(Node node) {
    int oldFreq = node.freq;

    DoublyLinkedList oldList = freqMap.get(oldFreq);

    oldList.remove(node);

    if (oldFreq == minFreq && oldList.size == 0) {
        minFreq++;
    }

    node.freq++;

    freqMap
        .computeIfAbsent(node.freq, k -> new DoublyLinkedList())
        .addToHead(node);
}
```

This does:

```text
1. Remove node from old frequency list.
2. If old list was minFreq and became empty, increase minFreq.
3. Increase node frequency.
4. Add node to new frequency list.
```

---

# Why minFreq = 1 for New Node?

Every new node starts with frequency `1`.

```java
this.freq = 1;
```

So after inserting a new node, the minimum frequency in the cache must become `1`.

That is why we do:

```java
minFreq = 1;
```

---

# Complexity

```text
get(): O(1)
put(): O(1)

Space Complexity: O(capacity)
```

HashMap access is `O(1)`, and adding/removing from a doubly linked list is also `O(1)`.
